fields.description:
Currently when using the Docker run command, it is only possible to mount the $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIRECTORY. It would be good to allow support for mounting other directories under the $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIRECTORY

Allow for mounting directories such as:

{code}
#!
$ docker run -v $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIR/app:/app my-container:version
{code}

As per this discussion here. Including a few example use-cases: https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Bitbucket-questions/Re-Re-Bitbucket-pipelines-how-can-I-map-a-volume-to-do/qaq-p/703437/comment-id/22253#M22253

Since the degradation of your services we are unable to edit or create our team&#x27;s wiki pages on  bitbucket. Since the status page shows that everything is up and running, I am rising this issue. Problem has occured since 9.1.2018. Last try gave me this code:

{code}
#!python
1eca4f48dd5d40d08ceadd798183f607
{code}

* *Repository:* https://bitbucket.org/Giron/joynerbe

Every try ends with the same result - "Something went wrong". Thank you in advance for taking a look into the issue.

S/w testers are not developers, instead of granting them access to code repo, we have created separate repo only to submit issues.

But we are not able to cross reference those issues from main code repo. For example following doesn&#x27;t close the issue in &#x27;issue-only-repo&#x27;.

{code}
git commit -m &#x27;fixed issue-only-repo/issues#10 ...&#x27;
{code}

We are able to do that at github [https://help.github.com/articles/creating-an-issues-only-repository/|https://help.github.com/articles/creating-an-issues-only-repository/]

It will be good to implement same here.

Can&#x27;t view pull requests, can&#x27;t checkout branches.

{code}
#!
$ git checkout Story/ATG-6218
fatal: unable to access &#x27;https://bitbucket.org/naturacode/rede-natura-atg.git/&#x27;: The requested URL returned error: 500
Switched to branch &#x27;Story/ATG-6218&#x27;

$ git checkout story/ATG-6218
refrror: RPC failed; HTTP 500 curl 22 The requested URL returned error: 500 Internal Server Error
fatal: The remote end hung up unexpectedly
Switched to branch &#x27;story/ATG-6218&#x27;
Your branch and &#x27;origin/story/ATG-6218&#x27; have diverged,
and have 21 and 22 different commits each, respectively.
  (use "git pull" to merge the remote branch into yours)
fatal: unable to access &#x27;https://bitbucket.org/naturacode/rede-natura-atg.git/&#x27;: The requested URL returned error: 500
{code}

It seems like it is not possible to do something like this:

{code}
#!yaml

image:
  name: $BUILD_IMAGE_NAME
  aws:
    access-key: $AWS_ACCESS_KEY
    secret-key: $AWS_SECRET_KEY
{code}

as pipelines fails with an error:

{code}
The ECR image name &#x27;name&#x27; in your bitbucket-pipelines.yml file is invalid. Expecting &#x27;<accountId>.dkr.ecr.<region>.amazonaws.com/image-name&#x27;
{code}

I&#x27;d like to be able to use an ENV var to specify image name in bitbucket-pipelines.yml

Per this community question: https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Bitbucket-questions/Bitbucket-pipelines-how-can-I-map-a-volume-to-docker-to-expose/qaq-p/686951#U695654

I&#x27;m unable to mount a volume to a Docker build in a BB Pipeline step:

{code}
#!bash

docker: Run command: docker run -v /opt/atlassian/pipelines/agent/build/packer-tmp/packer-docker516303980:/packer-files -d -i -t alpine:3.6 /bin/sh==> 
docker: Error running container: Docker exited with a non-zero exit status.==> 
docker: Stderr: docker: Error response from daemon: authorization denied by plugin pipelines: Command not supported.
{code}

The Pipelines&#x27; wiki says that the volumes can be mounted, but only in the repository&#x27;s directory. However, this is what I do here (by using {{${BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIR}}}), but I still get the error.

As a pipeline user I would like that I am able to run specific custom pipelines only on specific branches

that could be something like:

{code}
#!python

pipelines:
  custom:
    master <-- branch name
       deploy-to-prod:
          - step:
{code}

Our current SSH Pipelines instructions (https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/use-ssh-keys-in-bitbucket-pipelines-847452940.html) could be improved by adding permissions:

{code}
#!bash

vi ~/.ssh/authorized_keys


# Paste the public key from step 1 into this file, save and exit vi
# Set required permissions on the files

chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
{code}
